            <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed"><strong>Webflow:</strong> Visually stunning. The animations their designer spent months creating? Beautiful. But e-commerce features felt like an afterthought. Adding product bundles required custom code. Abandoned cart emails? Enterprise plans only.</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed"><strong>10Web:</strong> Used AI to recreate the Webflow design in WordPress/Elementor. Lost some of the fancy animations (WordPress doesn't do everything Webflow can do). But gained WooCommerce‚Äîfull-featured e-commerce with every plugin imaginable. Product bundles? $79 plugin. Abandoned cart? $49 plugin. Email marketing integration? Free plugin connected to Mailchimp.</p>
            <div class="bg-rose-100 border-l-[4px] border-rose-500 p-4 my-4">
              <p class="text-sm text-rose-900 font-medium"><strong>The punchline:</strong> They migrated to 10Web. Migration cost $18,000 (developer hours to recreate complex animations). But monthly costs dropped from $400+ to $45. 18-month break-even. And they got e-commerce features Webflow couldn't match at any price.</p>
            </div>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">Six months later? "We miss some of the Webflow animations. But we've made $127,000 in online sales we couldn't have done on Webflow without custom development. No regrets."</p>
            <div class="bg-pink-100 border-l-[4px] border-pink-500 p-4 my-4">
              <p class="text-sm text-pink-900 font-medium"><strong>The counterpoint:</strong> I advised a portfolio designer against 10Web. She doesn't sell products. She just needs to show her work beautifully. Webflow takes her 3 hours to build a stunning portfolio. 10Web/WooCommerce would be overkill and would complicate something simple. She stayed on Webflow. Loves it.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-fuchsia-100 border-l-[4px] border-fuchsia-500 p-4 my-4">
              <p class="text-sm text-fuchsia-900 font-medium"><strong>The truth:</strong> Webflow is the best tool for pure design work. 10Web is better when you need WordPress power and e-commerce. If you're selling products, 10Web's WooCommerce integration is unbeatable. If you're showcasing visual work, Webflow's design capabilities shine. Know what you need before you choose.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- REAL CASE STUDIES -->
